 || {{flag|United States}}\n|-\n| [[Basil Fernando]] and [[Asian Human Rights Commission|AHRC]] || {{flag|Hong Kong|name=Hong Kong SAR, China}}\n|-\n| [[Asma Jahangir]] || {{flag|Pakistan}}\n|-\n| [[Alan Rusbridger]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n| [[Edward Snowden]] || {{flag|United States}}\n|-\n! rowspan=5| 2015\n|-\n| [[Sheila Watt-Cloutier]] || {{flag|Canada}}\n|-\n| [[Tony deBrum]] || {{flag|Marshall Islands}}\n|-\n| [[Kasha Jacqueline Nabagesera]] || {{flag|Uganda}}\n|-\n| [[Gino Strada]] || {{flag|Italy}}\n|-\n! rowspan=5| 2016\n|-\n| [[Cumhuriyet]] || {{flag|Turkey}}\n|-\n| [[Syrian Civil Defense]] || {{flag|Syria}}\n|-\n| [[Mozn Hassan]] and [[Nazra for Feminist Studies]] || {{flag|Egypt}}\n|-\n| [[Svetlana Gannushkina]] || {{flag|Russia}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" |2017\n|-\n|[[Robert Bilott]] || {{flag|United States}}\n|-\n|[[Colin Gonsalves]] || {{flag|India}}\n|-\n|[[Khadija Ismayilova]] || {{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n|-\n|[[Yetnebersh Nigussie]] || {{flag|Ethiopia}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" |2018\n|-\n|[[Thelma Aldana]], [[Iv\u00e1n Vel\u00e1squez G\u00f3mez|Iv\u00e1n Vel\u00e1squez]] || {{flag|Guatemala}} {{flag|Colombia}}\n|-\n|[[Yacouba Sawadogo]] || {{flag|Burkina Faso}}\n|-\n|[[Abdullah al-Hamid]], [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani]], [[Waleed_Abulkhair|Walid Abu al-Chair]] || {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n|-\n|[[Tony Rinaudo]] || {{flag|Australia}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" |2019\n|-\n|[[Greta Thunberg]] || {{flag|Sweden}} \n|-\n|[[Aminatou Haidar]] || {{flag|Western Sahara}}\n|-\n|[[Davi Kopenawa Yanomami]] || {{flag|Brazil}}\n|-\n|[[Guo Jianmei]] || {{flag|China}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Right livelihood]]\n* [[List of awards for contributions to society]]\n* [[List of environmental awards]] \n* [[List of human rights awards]]\n* [[List of humanitarian and service awards]]\n* [[List of civil awards and decorations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Pathiravitana, S. (2007-11-08). ''A Great Son of Lanka''. Sri Lanka Daily News, 8 November 2007. A history of the award. Retrieved on 2008-06-03 from https://web.archive.org/web/20080110104454/http://www.dailynews.lk/2007/11/08/fea01.asp.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/}}\n*[http://www.democracynow.org/2010/9/16/right_livelihood_laureates_from_croatia_thailand Right Livelihood Laureates Discuss Their Battles for Social Justice] \u2013 video report by ''[[Democracy Now!]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Awards established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Humanitarian and service awards]]\n[[Category:Foundations based in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Peace awards]]\n[[Category:Right Livelihood Award laureates| ]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Human rights awards]]\n[[Category:Governance and civic leadership awards]]\n[[Category:Awards for contributions to society]]\n[[Category:Environmental awards]]\n[[Category:Civil awards and decorations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Award for solutions to challenges facing the world}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = Right Livelihood Award\n| current_awards =\n| image          = Right Livelihood Award.png\n| alt            =\n| caption        =\n| description    = \"practical and exemplary solutions to the most urgent challenges facing the world today\"\n| presenter      = Right Livelihood Award Foundation\n| host           =\n| date           = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location       =\n| country        = [[Sweden]]\n| year           = 1980\n| website        = [https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/ rightlivelihoodaward.org]\n}}\n[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-1.jpg|thumb|The award ceremony in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] in 2009]]\n[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-7.jpg|thumb|The 2009 award is presented to [[David Suzuki]] by [[Jakob von Uexkull]] (right) and European Commissioner [[Margot Wallstr\u00f6m]] (left)]]\n\nThe '''Right Livelihood Award''' is an international award to \"honour and support those offering practical and exemplary answers to the most urgent challenges facing us today.\"<ref name=\"MFA\"/> The prize was established in 1980 by [[Germans|German]]-Swedish [[philanthropist]] [[Jakob von Uexkull]], and is presented annually in early December.<ref>Jawetz, Pincas. [http://www.sustainabilitank.info/2009/10/13/the-alternate-nobels-right-livelihood-awards-2009-also-announced-by-sweden/ 30th Right Livelihood Awards: Wake-up calls to secure our common future.] ''SustainabiliTank.'' 13 Oct. 2009.</ref> An international jury, invited by the five regular Right Livelihood Award board members, decides the awards in such fields as [[environmentalism|environmental protection]], [[human rights]], [[sustainable development]], [[health]], [[education]], and [[peace]].<ref name=\"Thorpe\" /> The prize money is shared among the winners, usually numbering four, and is [[Euro|EUR]] 200,000.<ref name=about>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html About the Right Livelihood Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061052/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html |date=2011-08-11 }}. Accessed October 26, 2010.</ref> Very often one of the four laureates receives an honorary award, which means that the other three share the prize money.<ref name=\"Thorpe\"/>\n\nAlthough it is promoted as an '''\"Alternative Nobel Prize\"''',<ref name=\"BBC-7647718\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7647718.stm |title= Indians win 'alternative Nobel' |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 2 October 2008 |work= |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,2144,3683051,00.html |title= Peace and Social Justice Workers Receive Alternative Nobel Prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 1 October 2008 |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |title= Global activists honoured with 'Alternative Nobel' prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |work=[[The Local]] |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002043224/https://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |archivedate=2 October 2010|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-11445709\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11445709 |title= Israeli doctors' group wins 'alternative' Nobel prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"FAZ\">{{cite news |url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubBF80E0BCB9BE4D30B11BB6D4CFBD637E/Doc~E2D25260C587C4598BA448B223C540BEC~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html |title= Alternativer Nobelpreis: Kampf gegen Klimawandel, Armut, Kriege ausgezeichnet |date= 13 October 2009 |newspaper=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> it is not a [[Nobel prize]] (i.e., a prize created by [[Alfred Nobel]]). It does not have any organizational ties at all to the awarding institutions of the Nobel Prize or the Nobel Foundation, unlike the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]], which is not technically a Nobel prize but is administered by the Nobel Foundation.\n\nHowever, the Right Livelihood Award is sometimes popularly associated with the Nobel prizes. The Right Livelihood Award committee arranged for awards to be made in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] the day before the Nobel prizes and the economics prize are also awarded in [[Stockholm]]. However, the Right Livelihood Awards are understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name=\"FAZ\"/> The establishment of the award followed a failed attempt to have the Nobel Foundation create new prizes in the areas of environmental protection, sustainable development and human rights. The prize has been awarded to a diverse group of people and organisations, including [[Wangari Maathai]], [[Astrid Lindgren]], [[Bianca Jagger]], [[Mordechai Vanunu]], [[Leopold Kohr]], [[Arna Mer-Khamis]], [[Felicia Langer]], [[Petra Kelly]], [[Survival International]], [[Amy Goodman]], [[Memorial (society)|Memorial]], [[Edward Snowden]] and [[Greta Thunberg]].\n\n==Ceremony==\nSince 1985, the ceremony has taken place in [[Stockholm]]'s old Parliament building, in the days before the traditional Nobel prizes are awarded in the same city. A group of Swedish Parliamentarians from different parties host the ceremony; in 2009 European Commissioner [[Margot Wallstr\u00f6m]] co-hosted the ceremony. However, in 2014 when it became public that one of the recipients of the 2014 prize was [[whistleblower]] [[Edward Snowden]], the ceremonial group was disinvited from the Ministry for Foreign Affairs building in Stockholm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edward Snowden inte v\u00e4lkommen till UD|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/article19588815.ab|accessdate=24 September 2014|work=Aftonbladet|publisher=Aftonbladet|date=24 September 2014|ref=16}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, marking the 40th anniversary of the foundation of the Award, the ceremony was held at [[Cirkus (Stockholm)|Cirkus]] before a live audience of more than 1,200 people. World-renowned artists such as [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Ane Brun]] were among the night's performers.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 Right Livelihood Award Presentation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W8Su3koxFOw|language=en|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Nature of the award==\nSome media refer to the prize as the ''Alternative Nobel Prize'',<ref name=Thorpe>{{cite book|last1=Thorpe|first1=Edgar|last2=Thorpe|first2=Showick|title=Guide to the Combined Defence Services Exam|publisher=Pearson Education|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-317-0074-7|page=26|chapter=General Awareness: Right Livelihood Award}}</ref> and the prize is frequently understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name=\"FAZ\"/>\n\nThe prize differs significantly from the [[Nobel Prize]]s:\n*it is not a fulfillment of [[Alfred Nobel]]'s bequest and thus not one of Nobel's own prizes;\n*it has an open nomination process (anyone can nominate anyone else, except close relatives or their own organizations);<ref>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/propose_a_candidate.html Right Livelihood Award: Proposals & Selection Process]. Accessed January 24, 2010.</ref>\n*it is not limited to specific categories;<ref name=about/>\n*the prize money is considerably lower than that of the Nobel Prize. Currently it is \u20ac200,000 compared to about \u20ac1,000,000 for a Nobel Prize;\n*the funds for the prizes now come from donations<ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |title=The 2013 Right Livelihood Laureates announced |author=Ministry for Foreign Affairs |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-14 |publisher=Government Offices of Sweden |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303235727/http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |archivedate=3 March 2014 }}</ref> while the Nobel Prizes come from the revenue of Alfred Nobel's fortune. The [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] (which is technically not a Nobel Prize) is financed by the [[Sveriges Riksbank]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Rightlivelihoodaward.jpg|thumb|right|150 px|The 1994 award given to [[Hanumappa Sudarshan|Dr. Sudarshan]] photographed in [[BR Hills]]]]\n[[Carl Wolmar Jakob von Uexk\u00fcll|Jakob von&nbsp;Uexk\u00fcll]], a philanthropist, sold his stamp collection worth one million US&nbsp;dollars, which provided the initial funding for the award. Before establishing the award in 1980, von&nbsp;Uexkull had tried to persuade the [[Nobel Foundation]] to establish new prizes to be awarded together with the Nobel Prizes. He suggested new prize categories to be created: one in ecology and one in development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html |title=Right Livelihood Award: History - Setting up the 'Alternative Nobel Prize' |publisher=Rightlivelihood.org |accessdate=2012-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829121254/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html |archivedate=2012-08-29 }}</ref> Like the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel|Nobel Economics Prize]], this would have been possible with an amendment to the Nobel Foundation statutes and funding of the prize amount completely separate from Nobel's fortune. The Nobel Prize amount was 880,000 Swedish kronor at that time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/about/amounts.html |title=The Nobel Prize Amounts |publisher=Nobelprize.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-28}}</ref> which corresponded to 195,000 US&nbsp;dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://currate.com/historical-exchange-rates.php|title=according to historical exchange rate from}}</ref> However, as a result of the debate that followed the establishment of the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel]] (first awarded in 1969), the Nobel Foundation had decided not to associate the Nobel Prize with any additional awards, so von&nbsp;Uexk\u00fcll's proposal was rejected.<ref name=\"ttdn\">TT-DN (2003-10-02). ''Alternativt Nobelpris delas p\u00e5 fem''. Dagens Nyheter, \"Publicerat 2003-10-02 10:08\". Retrieved from http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=188389. {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1980-2019, the foundation presented awards to 178 Laureates from 70 countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/honour/about-the-right-livelihood-award/|title=About the Right Livelihood Award|website=The Right Livelihood Award|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Its self-described purpose is to bestow prizes and thus publicize the work of recipients' local solutions to worldwide problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620110022/http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html|url-status=dead|title=Right Livelihood Award history|archivedate=June 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Laureates<ref name=\"Right Livelihood Award Laureates\">{{cite web |title=Laureates |url=https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/laureates/ |website=Right Livelihood Foundation |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year !!Laureates !! Country\n|-\n! rowspan=3| 1980\n|-\n| [[Hassan Fathy]] ||{{flag|Egypt|1972}}\n|-\n| [[Plenty International]] / [[Stephen Gaskin]]||{{flag|United States}}<br>{{flag|Guatemala}}<br>{{flag|Lesotho|1966}}\n|-\n! rowspan=4| 1981\n|-\n| [[Mike Cooley (engineer)|Mike Cooley]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n| [[Bill Mollison]] || {{flag|Australia}}\n|-\n| [[Patrick van Rensburg]] / Education with Production || {{flag|Botswana}}<br />{{flag|South Africa|1928}}\n|-\n! rowspan=6| 1982\n|-\n| [[Erik Dammann]] / Future in Our Hands || {{flag|Norway}}\n|-\n| [[Anwar Fazal]] || {{flag|Malaysia}}\n|-\n| [[Petra Kelly]] || {{flag|West Germany}}\n|-\n| [[Participatory Institute for Development Alternatives]] || {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|-\n| [[Sir George Trevelyan, 4th Baronet|Sir George Trevelyan, Bt]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=5| 1983\n|-\n| [[Leopold Kohr]] || {{flag|Austria}}\n|-\n| [[Amory Lovins]] and [[Hunter Lovins]] / [[Rocky Mountain Institute]] || {{flag|United States}}\n|-\n| [[Manfred Max-Neef]] / CEPAUR || {{flag|Chile}}\n|-\n| High Chief [[Ibedul Gibbons]] and the People of Belau || {{flag|Palau}}\n|-\n! rowspan=5| 1984\n|-\n| [[Imane Khalifeh]] || {{flag|Lebanon}}\n|-\n| [[Self-Employed Women's Association]] / [[Ela Bhatt]] || {{flag|India}}\n|-\n| [[Winefreda Geonzon]] / [[Free Legal Assistance Volunteers' Association]] (FREE LAVA) || {{flag|Philippines|1936}}\n|-\n| [[Wangari Maathai]] / [[Green Belt Movement]] || {{flag|Kenya}}\n|-\n! rowspan=6| 1985\n|-\n| [[Theo Van Boven]] || {{flag|Netherlands}}\n|-\n| [[Cary Fowler]] ([[Rural Advancement Fund International]])|| {{flag|United States}}\n|-\n| [[Pat Moone